---
description: Defines ownership boundaries, dependency rules, and communication between modules in the LexMastery Flutter application.

alwaysApply: true
---

# Module Boundaries

LexMastery is a modular application.

Every module owns one business capability.

Modules must remain independent.

Never merge unrelated business domains.

---

# Business Modules

The official business modules are:

authentication

onboarding

dashboard

courses

learning

flashcards

quizzes

mock_exams

ai_tutor

ai_instructor

diagnostics

comparative_law

analytics

notifications

profile

settings

accessibility

Each module should evolve independently.

---

# Core Module

The Core module owns:

Networking

Authentication Infrastructure

Analytics

Theme

Routing

Dependency Injection

Storage

Logging

Errors

Constants

Environment

Utilities

Core owns infrastructure.

Core never owns business logic.

---

# Shared Module

Shared contains reusable presentation components.

Examples:

Buttons

Cards

Dialogs

Inputs

Badges

Spacing

Typography

Icons

Animations

Extensions

Validators

A shared component must be reused by at least three features.

Otherwise,

keep it inside the feature.

---

# Feature Ownership

Each feature owns:

Presentation

Domain

Data

Routes

Widgets

Controllers

Repositories

Use Cases

Tests

Assets specific to that feature

No other feature may modify these directly.

---

# Communication Rules

Features do not communicate directly.

Allowed communication:

↓

Repository Interfaces

↓

Core Services

↓

Events

↓

Navigation

Forbidden:

Feature A imports Feature B.

Never create tight coupling.

---

# Ownership Rule

Every file has one owner.

Every class has one owner.

Every responsibility has one owner.

Avoid shared ownership.

---

# Widget Ownership

Widgets should stay inside their feature until reused.

Rule:

Used once → Feature

Used twice → Feature

Used three or more times → Shared

Never prematurely move widgets to Shared.

---

# Repository Ownership

Repositories belong to the feature.

AuthenticationRepository

belongs only to

Authentication.

CourseRepository

belongs only to

Courses.

AIRepository

belongs only to

AI Tutor.

---

# Controller Ownership

One screen

↓

One Controller

Never share controllers across unrelated screens.

---

# State Ownership

State belongs to the feature.

Never create global mutable state.

Global state is limited to:

Authentication

Theme

Locale

Connectivity

User Session

Everything else remains local.

---

# API Ownership

Every endpoint belongs to one feature.

Example:

/auth/*

↓

Authentication

/courses/*

↓

Courses

/ai/*

↓

AI Tutor

Never mix endpoints between repositories.

---

# Asset Ownership

Global assets

↓

assets/

Feature-specific illustrations

↓

feature/assets/

Do not duplicate assets.

---

# Testing Ownership

Every feature owns:

Unit Tests

Widget Tests

Golden Tests

Integration Tests

Tests should remain alongside the feature.

---

# Dependency Rules

Allowed:

Feature

↓

Core

Feature

↓

Shared

Presentation

↓

Domain

↓

Data

Forbidden:

Feature

↓

Feature

Presentation

↓

Presentation

Domain

↓

Flutter UI

---

# Package Ownership

Infrastructure packages belong to Core.

UI packages belong to Shared.

Business packages belong to Features.

Never mix responsibilities.

---

# Analytics Ownership

Each feature emits analytics.

Core records analytics.

Features never talk directly to Firebase.

---

# Error Ownership

Features define business failures.

Core defines infrastructure failures.

UI converts failures into user-friendly messages.

---

# Cursor Instructions

Before creating any file:

1.

Identify the business module.

2.

Identify the owner.

3.

Identify the correct layer.

4.

Verify the dependency direction.

5.

Only then generate the file.

Never create files outside the correct owner.

Architecture consistency is mandatory.